 2008 |url-status=dead  }}\n* Setty, E.D. and Ross, E.L. (1987), \"A Case Study in Applied Education in Rural India\", ''Community Development Journal'', 22 ('''2'''): 120\u2013129, Oxford University Press.\n* Sripati, V. and Thiruvengadam, A.K. (2004), \"India: Constitutional Amendment Making The Right to Education a Fundamental Right\", ''International Journal of Constitutional Law'', 2 ('''1'''): 148\u2013158, Oxford University Press.\n* Vrat, Prem (2006), \"Indian Institutes of Technology\", ''Encyclopedia of India (vol. 2)'' edited by Stanley Wolpert, 229\u2013231, Thomson Gale: {{ISBN|0-684-31351-0}}.\n* Desai, Sonalde, Amaresh Dubey, B.L. Joshi, Mitali Sen, Abusaleh Shariff and Reeve Vanneman. 2010. [https://web.archive.org/web/20120623054931/http://ihds.umd.edu/IHDS_files/06HDinIndia.pdf India Human Development in India: Challenges for a Society in Transition. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.]\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n<!--NO COMMERCIAL LINKS PLEASE-->\n*[http://mhrd.gov.in/ Ministry of Human Resource Development]\n*[http://www.mospi.nic.in/1-education Education statistics from the Ministry of Statistics & Programme Implementation]\n\n{{India topics}}\n{{Asia topic|Education in}}\n{{Education in India}}\n{{Portal bar|Education|India}}\n\n[[Category:Education in India| ]]\n", "name_user": "KartikMistry", "label": "safe", "comment": "Unrelated.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Education_in_India"}
{"title_page": "List of California state prisons", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[Image:SanQuentinSP.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25|[[San Quentin State Prison]], California's oldest detention facility.]]\n\nThis is a '''list of state prisons in California''' administered by the [[California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation]] (CDCR).<ref>{{cite web |author=Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation |title=Adult Facilities and Locations |url=https://www.cdcr.ca.gov/facility-locator/adult-institutions/ |publisher=California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation |accessdate=2020-03-29 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329172929/https://www.cdcr.ca.gov/facility-locator/adult-institutions/ |archivedate=2020-03-29}}</ref> This is a list of adult facilities, and does not include [[List of California county jails|county jails]], [[California Division of Juvenile Justice]] facilities, [[California Conservation Fire Camps]], or [[Federal Bureau of Prisons facilities in California]].\n\nAs of August 2016, California has about 6,000 state prisoners in two privately operated correctional centers in Arizona and Mississippi to relieve [[prison overcrowding]]:  the [[La Palma Correctional Facility]], and the [[Tallahatchie County Correctional Facility]].<ref>{{cite web | author=Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation | title=Housing Inmates Out-of-State | url=http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Visitors/CA_Out_Of_State_Facilities.html | publisher=State of California | date=2009 | accessdate=2016-08-18}}</ref>\n\nThe state also contracts with the [[GEO Group]] to operate one 700-bed in-state facility, the [[Golden State Medium Community Correctional Facility]] in [[McFarland, California]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Golden State Modified Community Correctional Facility|url=http://www.geogroup.com/Maps/LocationDetails/45|accessdate=2016-08-21|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828130054/http://www.geogroup.com/maps/locationdetails/45|archivedate=2016-08-28|publisher=The GEO Group}}</ref> and leases and operates another facility, the [[California City Correctional Center]], which is owned by [[Corrections Corporation of America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cca.com/facilities/california-city-correctional-center#|title=CoreCivic: Better the Public Good|website=Cca.com|accessdate=25 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdcr.ca.gov/facility-locator/adult-institutions/|title=Adult Institutions List|website=California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>==\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Avenal State Prison]] (ASP)(est. capacity 4,346)\n* [[California City Correctional Facility]] (CAC) (est. capacity 2,496)\n* [[California Correctional Center]] (CCC) (est. capacity 4,888)\n* [[California Correctional Institution]] (CCI) (est. capacity 4,074)\n* [[California Institution for Men]] (CIM) (est. capacity 3,815)\n* [[California Health Care Facility]] (CHCF) (est. capacity 2,840)\n* [[California Institution for Women]] (CIW) (est. capacity 1,190)\n* [[California Medical Facility]] (CMF) (est. capacity 2,626)\n* [[California Men's Colony]] (CMC) (est. capacity 4,021)\n* [[California Rehabilitation Center]] (CRC) (est. capacity 3,573)\n* [[California State Prison, Centinela]] (CEN) (est. capacity 3,606)\n* [[California State Prison, Corcoran]] (COR) (est. capacity 3,351)\n* [[California State Prison, Los Angeles County]] (LAC) (est. capacity 3,334)\n* [[California State Prison, Sacramento]] (SAC) (est. capacity 2,270)\n* [[California State Prison, Solano]] (SOL) (est. capacity 4,575)\n* [[California Substance Abuse Treatment Facility and State Prison, Corcoran]] (SATF) (est. capacity 6,006)\n* [[Calipatria State Prison]] (CAL) (est. capacity 3,699)\n* [[Central California Women's Facility]] (CCWF)(est. capacity 2,944)\n* [[Chuckawalla Valley State Prison]] (CVSP) (est. capacity 3,018)\n* [[Correctional Training Fac