{"title_page": "Nadesalingam family asylum claims", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''Kokilapathmapriya Nadesalingam''' (Priya) and '''Nadesalingam Murugappan''' (Nades)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-au/news/australia/theyre-not-refugees-theyre-not-owed-protection-peter-dutton-says-asylum-seeker-sri-lankan-family-will-be-deported-despite-last-minute-reprieve-and-protests/ar-AAGwvh9?li=AAgfYrC&%252525253Bocid=mailsignoutmd|title='They're not refugees, they're not owed protection': Peter Dutton says asylum seeker Sri Lankan family WILL be deported despite last-minute reprieve and protests|website=www.msn.com}}</ref> are two [[Sri Lanka]]n [[Sri Lankan Tamils|Tamil]]s seeking [[asylum in Australia]]. The couple married in Australia and have two Australian-born children. Until their detention by [[Australian Border Force]] in March 2018, the family was resident in the central Queensland town of [[Biloela]]. The cause of the couple and their children has been supported by some residents of Biloela as well as asylum-seeker advocates.<ref name=\"Bowling\">{{cite news |last1=Bowling |first1=Mark |title=Biloela community makes fresh moves to keep Tamil family in town after Sri Lanka terror attack |url=http://catholicleader.com.au/uncategorized/biloela-community-makes-fresh-moves-to-keep-tamil-family-in-town-after-sri-lanka-terror-attack |accessdate=29 August 2019 |work=The Catholic Leader |date=2 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Migration==\nPriya and Nades were both residents in Sri Lanka during the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]] which started in 1983 and formally ended in 2009 with the Sri Lankan Army defeating the separatist [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]] (LTTE). Nades claimed to have been forced to join the LTTE in 2001 and as a result was harassed by Sri Lankan government authorities.<ref name=\"Pengilley001\">{{cite news |last1=Pengilley |first1=Victoria |title=Tamil asylum seeker family from Biloela could be undone by father's travel history and refugee activism, immigration lawyer says |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-09-02/biloela-tamil-family-melbourne-federal-circuit-court-hearing/11468874 |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=2 September 2019}}</ref> The Australian government claim that Nades was able to freely travel to Kuwait and Qatar for work between 2004 and 2010 and therefore was not of concern to Sri Lankan authorities.<ref name=\"Pengilley001\" /> [[Damien Kingsbury]], an academic specialising in international politics, stated even though the civil war had ended Sri Lanka was still dangerous for some minorities, stating \"The environment is changing and it's never been particularly favourable to Tamils but it looks like it's changing back to a more draconian environment\".<ref name=\"Pengilley001\" /> Another immigration lawyer, Simon Jeans, claimed that the family had not been truthful in visa applications and said evidence suggested they came to Australia as economic refugees.<ref name=\"Pengilley001\" />\n\nNades arrived at [[Christmas Island]] on a [[people smuggler]] boat in 2012. Priya arrived at [[Cocos Islands]] on another people smuggler boat in 2013.<ref name=\"Minister2018\">{{cite press release |date=21 December 2018 |last=Dutton |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Dutton |title=Sri Lankan family pay people smugglers thousands cost Australian taxpayers millions |url=https://minister.homeaffairs.gov.au/peterdutton/Pages/sri-Lankan-family-pay-people-smugglers-thousands-cost-australian-taxpayers-millions.aspx|publisher=[[Minister for Home Affairs (Australia)|Minister for Home Affairs]] |access-date=4 September 2019}} </ref> Both claimed to be refugees on the grounds that they faced persecution in Sri Lanka. Both were granted temporary bridging visas.<ref name=\"Hope\">{{cite news |last1=Hope |first1=Zach |title=Dutton says Tamil family doesn't deserve Australia's protection |url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/she-was-screaming-family-s-deportation-stopped-by-last-minute-injunction-20190829-p52m84.html |accessdate=30 August 2019 |work=Sydney Morning Herald |date=30 August 2019}}</ref> The couple first met in Australia and married in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/tamil-family-fighting-to-stay-in-australia-to-learn-outcome-of-last-ditch-legal-bid-20190904-p52nq0.html |title=Tamil family granted two more days in last-ditch legal bid to stay in Australia |first=Rachel |last=Eddie |first2=Simone Fox |last2=Koob |date=4 September 2019 |newspaper=[[The Age]] |accessdate=4 September 2019}}</ref> They subsequently had two children, both born in Australia.<ref name=\"ABC20190830\">{{cite news |title=Who are the Tamil family from Biloela and why are they being deported? |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-30/who-are-tamil-family-from-biloela-why-are-they-being-deported/11463276 |accessdate=30 August 2019| date = 30 August 2019 |work=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref> They settled in [[Biloela]] where Nades worked in the local [[abattoir]].<ref name=\"Pengilley\">{{cite news |last1=Pengilley |first1=Victoria |title=Deportation of Tamil asylum seeker family interrupted midair by last-minute injunction |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-29/tamil-asylum-seeker-family-from-biloela-facing-deportation/11463176 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |work=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=30 August 2019}}</ref> Nades was also a volunteer with the local [[Society of Saint Vincent de Paul]].<ref name=\"Stunzner\">{{cite news |last1=Stunzner |first1=Inga |last2=McCosker |first2=Amy |last3=Robinson |first3=Paul |title=Asylum seeker family removed 'without warning' at dawn in central Queensland, Tamil Refugee Council says |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-03-12/asylum-seeker-family-removed-at-dawn-biloela-central-qld/9538368 |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref>\n\n==Detention==\nThe family were taken into custody by Australian Border Force personnel from their home in Biloela in March 2018 and taken to the [[Melbourne Immigration Transit Accommodation]] facility in [[Broadmeadows, Victoria|Broadmeadows]], a suburb of Melbourne.<ref name=\"Hendry\">{{cite news |last1=Hendry |first1=Megan |title=Tamil asylum seeker family 'whisked away' for deportation draws massive community support |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-03-14/biloela-holds-vigil-for-sri-lankan-family-facing-deportation/9544860 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |work=ABCNews |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=30 August 2019}}</ref> While in detention in Melbourne, supporters of the family claimed that the couple and their children had been ill-treated and denied basic nutrition and health care.<ref name=\"Zhuang\">{{cite news |last1=Zhuang |first1=Yan |title=Family say two-year-old detainee 'recovering', government denies she was hurt |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/two-year-old-detainee-recovering-government-denies-she-was-injured-20190706-p524rm.html |accessdate=30 August 2019 |work=The Age |date=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, the [[Federal Court of Australia]] found that Priya was not eligible to stay in Australia, while Nades' rights of appeal were already extinguished.<ref name=\"Cox\">{{cite news |title=Tamil family lose appeal to stay in Australia |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/jun/21/tamil-family-lose-appeal-to-stay-in-australia |accessdate=30 August 2019 |work=Guardian Australia |date=21 June 2018}}</ref> In the judgment, the judge noted that the civil war had ended in 2009, Nades had returned to Sri Lanka on three occasions during the civil war and found that there was \"no evidence to suggest [Nades'] family still living in Sri Lanka was at risk from authorities\".<ref name=\"ABC20190830\" /> Priya lodged an appeal with the [[Administrative Appeals Tribunal]]. This appeal was dismissed in December 2018, however the government was restrained from deporting the family until February 2019.<ref name=\"Davey\">{{cite news |last1=Davey |first1=Melissa |title=Tamil family's appeal to remain in Australia dismissed in federal court |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/dec/21/tamil-familys-appeal-to-remain-in-australia-dismissed-by-federal-court |accessdate=30 August 2019 |work=Guardian Australia |date=21 December 2019}}</ref> A further application by the couple to seek special leave to [[High Court of Australia]] to hear an appeal of the Federal Court decision was refused in May 2019.<ref name=\"Flatley\">{{cite news |last1=Flatley |first1=Christine |last2=McElroy |first2=Nicholas |title=Tamil family loses High Court appeal |url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6122877/tamil-family-loses-high-court-appeal/?cs=14231 |accessdate=29 August 2019 |work=Canberra Times |date=14 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAn attempt to deport the couple, and their Australian-born children, on 29 August 2019 was prevented by an injunction lodged by the solicitors while the plane taking the family to Sri Lanka was in mid-air. This injunction was granted as the youngest child had not yet been assessed for a protection visa.<ref name=\"Smith\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Rohan |last2=Graham |first2=Ben |title=Dutton lashes out at 'disgusting' criticism over Tamil asylum family secretly flown to Christmas Island |url=https://www.news.com.au/national/courts-law/tamil-family-facing-deportation-asks-peter-dutton-to-open-your-heart/news-story/b60d975bb2cf8bde605a78fdc692b42e |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=News.com.au |publisher=News Limited |date=1 September 2019}}</ref> The injunction forced the plane to land in [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]].<ref name=\"Hope\" /> The family were then taken to [[Christmas Island Immigration Reception and Processing Centre]].<ref name=\"Doherty\">{{cite news |last1=Doherty |first1=Ben |title=Biloela Tamil asylum-seeker family moved to Christmas Island |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/aug/31/biloela-tamil-asylum-seeker-family-moved-to-christmas-island |accessdate=1 September 2019 |work=Guardian Australia |date=31 August 2019}}</ref> On 19 September 2019, the Federal Court ruled that the younger daughter (and hence the family) should remain in Australia until the case goes to a final hearing at a date to be determined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/sep/19/biloela-tamil-family-deportation-case-asylum-seekers-expected-to-learn-fate-today|title=Biloela Tamil family deportation case: asylum seekers can stay until final hearing|first=Josh|last=Taylor|date=September 19, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> In April 2020, the Federal Court ruled that Immigration Minister [[David Coleman (Australian politician)|David Coleman]] had taken a procedural step to consider using ministerial powers to allow the youngest daughter, two-year-old Tharunicaa, to apply for a visa, which now needs to be finalised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/tamil-family-on-christmas-island-win-federal-court-case-20200417-p54ko7.html|title=Tamil family on Christmas Island win Federal Court case|first=Rachel|last=Eddie|date=17 April 2020|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-17/biloela-tamil-family-decision-in-federal-court/12156380 | title=Tamil girl 'not afforded procedural fairness' in Biloela family's asylum bid, Federal Court rules |first=Megan |last=Hendry |date=17 April 2020 |work=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reaction==\nPriya and Nades' wish to stay in Australia has been supported by some members of the Biloela community as well as refugee and asylum seeker advocates.<ref name=\"Doherty001\">{{cite news |last1=Doherty |first1=Ben |title=immigration and asylum 'We're a polite town': rage in Biloela as Tamil family's fate in Peter Dutton's hands |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/aug/31/we-implore-them-the-biloela-tamil-family-and-their-five-day-reprieve-from-deportation |accessdate=1 September 2019 |work=Guardian Australia}}</ref>\n\n[[Anthony Albanese]], leader of the opposition Australian Labor Party has supported granting permanent residency to the family stating \"These people should be settled here in Australia. It won't undermine the government's migration policies. It will simply say that this is a government that is prepared to listen to what the community are saying and saying so strongly\".<ref name=\"McGowan\">{{cite news |last1=McGowan |first1=Michael |last2=Martin |first2=Sarah |last3=Israel |first3=Janine |title=Albanese calls on PM to let Biloela Tamil family stay as rallies held across Australia |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/sep/01/australians-to-rally-to-save-biloela-tamil-family-from-deportation |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=Guardian Australia |date=1 September 2019}}</ref> Former National Party leader [[Barnaby Joyce]] also spoke in support noting that the Biloela community \"seem to be pretty enthused about keeping this family there ... I think we should also be listening to them.\"<ref name=\"McGowan\" /> \n\nThe [[Minister for Home Affairs]] [[Peter Dutton]] stated that the family's case was \"completely without merit in terms of their claim to be refugees\"<ref name=\"Bolger\">{{cite news |last1=Bolger |first1=Rosemary |title=Peter Dutton won't take 'moral lecture' on Tamil family detained on Christmas Island |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/peter-dutton-won-t-take-moral-lecture-on-tamil-family-detained-on-christmas-island |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=SBS News |publisher=Special Broadcasting Service |date=2 September 2019}}</ref> and \"I would like the family to accept that they are not refugees, they're not owed protection by our country\".<ref name=\"Hope\" /> Prime Minister [[Scott Morrison]] refused calls to intervene, stating \"they didn't come to the country in the appropriate way. They have not been found to have an asylum claim\" and \"to exercise intervention powers on this would be to send exactly the wrong message to those who are looking to sell tickets to vulnerable people looking to get on boats ...\"<ref name=\"Ferguson\">{{cite news |last1=Ferguson |first1=Richard |title=Scott Morrison: Tamil family has to leave |url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/dutton-tamil-asylum-family-can-never-remain/news-story/b6ed4b6fd2b5a79506b6d211224e7a92 |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=The Australian |publisher=News Limited |date=2 September 2019}}</ref> Morrison stated that the family remain eligible to lodge an application to migrate to Australia; \"they can make an application to come to Australia under the same processes as everyone else, anywhere else in the world. And I would hope they do.\"<ref name=\"Ferguson\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.hometobilo.com/ Home to Bilo] - Campaign website. Retrieved 2 September 2019\n\n{{Asylumaustralia}}\n\n[[Category:Immigration to Australia]]\n[[Category:2019 in Australia]]\n[[Category:2020 in Australia]]\n[[Category:Biloela]]\n[[Category:Tamil people]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan people]]\n[[Category:Right of asylum in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''Kokilapathmapriya Nadesalingam''' (Priya) and '''Nadesalingam Murugappan''' (Nades)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-au/news/australia/theyre-not-refugees-theyre-not-owed-protection-peter-dutton-says-asylum-seeker-sri-lankan-family-will-be-deported-despite-last-minute-reprieve-and-protests/ar-AAGwvh9?li=AAgfYrC&%252525253Bocid=mailsignoutmd|title='They're not refugees, they're not owed protection': Peter Dutton says asylum seeker Sri Lankan family WILL be deported despite last-minute reprieve and protests|website=www.msn.com}}</ref> are two [[Sri Lanka]]n [[Sri Lankan Tamils|Tamil]]s seeking [[asylum in Australia]]. The couple married in Australia and have two Australian-born children. Until their detention by [[Australian Border Force]] in March 2018, the family was resident in the central Queensland town of [[Biloela]]. The cause of the couple and their children has been supported by some residents of Biloela as well as asylum-seeker advocates.<ref name=\"Bowling\">{{cite news |last1=Bowling |first1=Mark |title=Biloela community makes fresh moves to keep Tamil family in town after Sri Lanka terror attack |url=http://catholicleader.com.au/uncategorized/biloela-community-makes-fresh-moves-to-keep-tamil-family-in-town-after-sri-lanka-terror-attack |accessdate=29 August 2019 |work=The Catholic Leader |date=2 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Migration==\nPriya and Nades were both resident in Sri Lanka during the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]] which started in 1983 and formally ended in 2009 with the Sri Lankan Army defeating the separatist [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]] (LTTE). Nades claimed to have been forced to join the LTTE in 2001 and as a result was harassed by Sri Lankan government authorities.<ref name=\"Pengilley001\">{{cite news |last1=Pengilley |first1=Victoria |title=Tamil asylum seeker family from Biloela could be undone by father's travel history and refugee activism, immigration lawyer says |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-09-02/biloela-tamil-family-melbourne-federal-circuit-court-hearing/11468874 |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=2 September 2019}}</ref> The Australian government claim that Nades was able to freely travel to Kuwait and Qatar for work between 2004 and 2010 and therefore was not of concern to Sri Lankan authorities.<ref name=\"Pengilley001\" /> [[Damien Kingsbury]], an academic specialising in international politics, stated even though the civil war had ended Sri Lanka was still dangerous for some minorities, stating \"The environment is changing and it's never been particularly favourable to Tamils but it looks like it's changing back to a more draconian environment\".<ref name=\"Pengilley001\" /> Another immigration lawyer, Simon Jeans, claimed that the family had not been truthful in visa applications and said evidence suggested they came to Australia as economic refugees.<ref name=\"Pengilley001\" />\n\nNades arrived at [[Christmas Island]] on a [[people smuggler]] boat in 2012. Priya arrived at [[Cocos Islands]] on another people smuggler boat in 2013.<ref name=\"Minister2018\">{{cite press release |date=21 December 2018 |last=Dutton |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Dutton |title=Sri Lankan family pay people smugglers thousands cost Australian taxpayers millions |url=https://minister.homeaffairs.gov.au/peterdutton/Pages/sri-Lankan-family-pay-people-smugglers-thousands-cost-australian-taxpayers-millions.aspx|publisher=[[Minister for Home Affairs (Australia)|Minister for Home Affairs]] |access-date=4 September 2019}} </ref> Both claimed to be refugees on the grounds that they faced persecution in Sri Lanka. Both were granted temporary bridging visas.<ref name=\"Hope\">{{cite news |last1=Hope |first1=Zach |title=Dutton says Tamil family doesn't deserve Australia's protection |url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/she-was-screaming-family-s-deportation-stopped-by-last-minute-injunction-20190829-p52m84.html |accessdate=30 August 2019 |work=Sydney Morning Herald |date=30 August 2019}}</ref> The couple first met in Australia and married in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/tamil-family-fighting-to-stay-in-australia-to-learn-outcome-of-last-ditch-legal-bid-20190904-p52nq0.html |title=Tamil family granted two more days in last-ditch legal bid to stay in Australia |first=Rachel |last=Eddie |first2=Simone Fox |last2=Koob |date=4 September 2019 |newspaper=[[The Age]] |accessdate=4 September 2019}}</ref> They subsequently had two children, both born in Australia.<ref name=\"ABC20190830\">{{cite news |title=Who are the Tamil family from Biloela and why are they being deported? |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-30/who-are-tamil-family-from-biloela-why-are-they-being-deported/11463276 |accessdate=30 August 2019| date = 30 August 2019 |work=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref> They settled in [[Biloela]] where Nades worked in the local [[abattoir]].<ref name=\"Pengilley\">{{cite news |last1=Pengilley |first1=Victoria |title=Deportation of Tamil asylum seeker family interrupted midair by last-minute injunction |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-29/tamil-asylum-seeker-family-from-biloela-facing-deportation/11463176 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |work=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=30 August 2019}}</ref> Nades was also a volunteer with the local [[Society of Saint Vincent de Paul]].<ref name=\"Stunzner\">{{cite news |last1=Stunzner |first1=Inga |last2=McCosker |first2=Amy |last3=Robinson |first3=Paul |title=Asylum seeker family removed 'without warning' at dawn in central Queensland, Tamil Refugee Council says |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-03-12/asylum-seeker-family-removed-at-dawn-biloela-central-qld/9538368 |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref>\n\n==Detention==\nThe family were taken into custody by Australian Border Force personnel from their home in Biloela in March 2018 and taken to the [[Melbourne Immigration Transit Accommodation]] facility in [[Broadmeadows, Victoria|Broadmeadows]], a suburb of Melbourne.<ref name=\"Hendry\">{{cite news |last1=Hendry |first1=Megan |title=Tamil asylum seeker family 'whisked away' for deportation draws massive community support |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-03-14/biloela-holds-vigil-for-sri-lankan-family-facing-deportation/9544860 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |work=ABCNews |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=30 August 2019}}</ref> While in detention in Melbourne, supporters of the family claimed that the couple and their children had been ill-treated and denied basic nutrition and health care.<ref name=\"Zhuang\">{{cite news |last1=Zhuang |first1=Yan |title=Family say two-year-old detainee 'recovering', government denies she was hurt |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/two-year-old-detainee-recovering-government-denies-she-was-injured-20190706-p524rm.html |accessdate=30 August 2019 |work=The Age |date=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, the [[Federal Court of Australia]] found that Priya was not eligible to stay in Australia, while Nades' rights of appeal were already extinguished.<ref name=\"Cox\">{{cite news |title=Tamil family lose appeal to stay in Australia |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/jun/21/tamil-family-lose-appeal-to-stay-in-australia |accessdate=30 August 2019 |work=Guardian Australia |date=21 June 2018}}</ref> In the judgment, the judge noted that the civil war had ended in 2009, Nades had returned to Sri Lanka on three occasions during the civil war and found that there was \"no evidence to suggest [Nades'] family still living in Sri Lanka was at risk from authorities\".<ref name=\"ABC20190830\" /> Priya lodged an appeal with the [[Administrative Appeals Tribunal]]. This appeal was dismissed in December 2018, however the government was restrained from deporting the family until February 2019.<ref name=\"Davey\">{{cite news |last1=Davey |first1=Melissa |title=Tamil family's appeal to remain in Australia dismissed in federal court |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/dec/21/tamil-familys-appeal-to-remain-in-australia-dismissed-by-federal-court |accessdate=30 August 2019 |work=Guardian Australia |date=21 December 2019}}</ref> A further application by the couple to seek special leave to [[High Court of Australia]] to hear an appeal of the Federal Court decision was refused in May 2019.<ref name=\"Flatley\">{{cite news |last1=Flatley |first1=Christine |last2=McElroy |first2=Nicholas |title=Tamil family loses High Court appeal |url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6122877/tamil-family-loses-high-court-appeal/?cs=14231 |accessdate=29 August 2019 |work=Canberra Times |date=14 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAn attempt to deport the couple, and their Australian-born children, on 29 August 2019 was prevented by an injunction lodged by the solicitors while the plane taking the family to Sri Lanka was in mid-air. This injunction was granted as the youngest child had not yet been assessed for a protection visa.<ref name=\"Smith\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Rohan |last2=Graham |first2=Ben |title=Dutton lashes out at 'disgusting' criticism over Tamil asylum family secretly flown to Christmas Island |url=https://www.news.com.au/national/courts-law/tamil-family-facing-deportation-asks-peter-dutton-to-open-your-heart/news-story/b60d975bb2cf8bde605a78fdc692b42e |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=News.com.au |publisher=News Limited |date=1 September 2019}}</ref> The injunction forced the plane to land in [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]].<ref name=\"Hope\" /> The family were then taken to [[Christmas Island Immigration Reception and Processing Centre]].<ref name=\"Doherty\">{{cite news |last1=Doherty |first1=Ben |title=Biloela Tamil asylum-seeker family moved to Christmas Island |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/aug/31/biloela-tamil-asylum-seeker-family-moved-to-christmas-island |accessdate=1 September 2019 |work=Guardian Australia |date=31 August 2019}}</ref> On 19 September 2019, the Federal Court ruled that the younger daughter (and hence the family) should remain in Australia until the case goes to a final hearing at a date to be determined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/sep/19/biloela-tamil-family-deportation-case-asylum-seekers-expected-to-learn-fate-today|title=Biloela Tamil family deportation case: asylum seekers can stay until final hearing|first=Josh|last=Taylor|date=September 19, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> In April 2020, the Federal Court ruled that Immigration Minister [[David Coleman (Australian politician)|David Coleman]] had taken a procedural step to consider using ministerial powers to allow the youngest daughter, two-year-old Tharunicaa, to apply for a visa, which now needs to be finalised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/tamil-family-on-christmas-island-win-federal-court-case-20200417-p54ko7.html|title=Tamil family on Christmas Island win Federal Court case|first=Rachel|last=Eddie|date=17 April 2020|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-17/biloela-tamil-family-decision-in-federal-court/12156380 | title=Tamil girl 'not afforded procedural fairness' in Biloela family's asylum bid, Federal Court rules |first=Megan |last=Hendry |date=17 April 2020 |work=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reaction==\nPriya and Nades' wish to stay in Australia has been supported by some members of the Biloela community as well as refugee and asylum seeker advocates.<ref name=\"Doherty001\">{{cite news |last1=Doherty |first1=Ben |title=immigration and asylum 'We're a polite town': rage in Biloela as Tamil family's fate in Peter Dutton's hands |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/aug/31/we-implore-them-the-biloela-tamil-family-and-their-five-day-reprieve-from-deportation |accessdate=1 September 2019 |work=Guardian Australia}}</ref>\n\n[[Anthony Albanese]], leader of the opposition Australian Labor Party has supported granting permanent residency to the family stating \"These people should be settled here in Australia. It won't undermine the government's migration policies. It will simply say that this is a government that is prepared to listen to what the community are saying and saying so strongly\".<ref name=\"McGowan\">{{cite news |last1=McGowan |first1=Michael |last2=Martin |first2=Sarah |last3=Israel |first3=Janine |title=Albanese calls on PM to let Biloela Tamil family stay as rallies held across Australia |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/sep/01/australians-to-rally-to-save-biloela-tamil-family-from-deportation |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=Guardian Australia |date=1 September 2019}}</ref> Former National Party leader [[Barnaby Joyce]] also spoke in support noting that the Biloela community \"seem to be pretty enthused about keeping this family there ... I think we should also be listening to them.\"<ref name=\"McGowan\" /> \n\nThe [[Minister for Home Affairs]] [[Peter Dutton]] stated that the family's case was \"completely without merit in terms of their claim to be refugees\"<ref name=\"Bolger\">{{cite news |last1=Bolger |first1=Rosemary |title=Peter Dutton won't take 'moral lecture' on Tamil family detained on Christmas Island |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/peter-dutton-won-t-take-moral-lecture-on-tamil-family-detained-on-christmas-island |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=SBS News |publisher=Special Broadcasting Service |date=2 September 2019}}</ref> and \"I would like the family to accept that they are not refugees, they're not owed protection by our country\".<ref name=\"Hope\" /> Prime Minister [[Scott Morrison]] refused calls to intervene, stating \"they didn't come to the country in the appropriate way. They have not been found to have an asylum claim\" and \"to exercise intervention powers on this would be to send exactly the wrong message to those who are looking to sell tickets to vulnerable people looking to get on boats ...\"<ref name=\"Ferguson\">{{cite news |last1=Ferguson |first1=Richard |title=Scott Morrison: Tamil family has to leave |url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/dutton-tamil-asylum-family-can-never-remain/news-story/b6ed4b6fd2b5a79506b6d211224e7a92 |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=The Australian |publisher=News Limited |date=2 September 2019}}</ref> Morrison stated that the family remain eligible to lodge an application to migrate to Australia; \"they can make an application to come to Australia under the same processes as everyone else, anywhere else in the world. And I would hope they do.\"<ref name=\"Ferguson\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.hometobilo.com/ Home to Bilo] - Campaign website. Retrieved 2 September 2019\n\n{{Asylumaustralia}}\n\n[[Category:Immigration to Australia]]\n[[Category:2019 in Australia]]\n[[Category:2020 in Australia]]\n[[Category:Biloela]]\n[[Category:Tamil people]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan people]]\n[[Category:Right of asylum in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Train of Knowledge", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nadesalingam_family_asylum_claims"}
{"title_page": "Sheep farming in Wales", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2014}}\n[[File:Curious Sheep - geograph.org.uk - 370174.jpg|thumb|right|Sheep in a field near [[Aberystwyth]]]]\n'''Sheep farming''' is important to the [[economy of Wales]]. Much of [[Wales]] is rural countryside and [[sheep]] are a very common feature in the landscape throughout the country. The [[woollen industry in Wales]] was a major contributor to the national economy, accounting for two-thirds of the nation's exports in 1660. Sheep farms are most often situated in the country's mountains and moorlands, where [[Herding dog|sheepdog]]s are employed to round up flocks. Sheep are also reared, however, along the south and west coasts of Wales.<ref name=\"Colson2011\">{{cite book|last=Colson|first=Mary|title=Wales|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FuK6lZf5Yh0C&pg=PA15|date=1 July 2011|publisher=Heinemann Library|isbn=978-1-4329-5242-6|pages=15\u2013}}</ref> In 2017 there were more than 10 million sheep in Wales and the total flock made up nearly 33% of the British total.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-42371973|title=Sheep numbers pass 10 million mark|date=15 December 2017|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> In 2011 sheep farming accounted for 80% of agriculture in Wales.{{cn|date=October 2018}}\n\n==Historical development==\n[[File:Badgerface ewe, Wales.jpg|right|thumb|A [[Badger Face Welsh Mountain]] ewe on [[Flat Holm]]]]\n[[File:Springtime scene - geograph.org.uk - 383776.jpg|thumb|Sheep and lambs near [[Brecon]] in early spring]]\nSheep farming is an ancient husbandry activity in rural parts of Wales where the climate and soil conditions were not suitable for growing crops other than [[oats]]. The activity is documented from mediaeval times, by which time white sheep probably imported by the Romans had interbred with native dark-fleeced types to produce varieties of [[Welsh Mountain sheep]]. Initially, sheep were bred for their milk and [[wool|fleece]]s, rather than their meat.<ref name=foodmonth/>\n\nBy the 13th century, sheep farming in  Wales had become a major industry and source of income, largely from wool, much of which was exported.  Large flocks of sheep were owned by [[Cistercian]] [[abbey]]s and [[monastery|monasteries]], such as those at [[Strata Florida]], [[Margam Abbey|Margam]], [[Basingwerk Abbey|Basingwerk]] and [[Tintern Abbey|Tintern]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XSE9AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA410&dq=wales+sheep+farming+history&hl=en&sa=X&ei=e0PMUcPaMMme0wW3uoHIAw&ved=0CDAQ6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=wales%20sheep&f=false  H.E. Hallam (ed.), ''The Agrarian history of England and Wales: 1042-1350'', pp.479-480]</ref><ref>[http://www.bahs.org.uk/AGHR/ARTICLES/06n1a1.pdf  R. A. Donkin, ''Cistercian Sheep, Farming and Wool-Sales in the Thirteenth Century'', The Agricultural History Review, vol.6, 1958, pp.2-8]. Retrieved 27 June 2013</ref>  The [[woollen industry in Wales]] was a major contributor to the national economy, accounting for two-thirds of the nation's exports in 1660.<ref name=Sheep/>  However, large-scale sheep rearing on the higher moors of Wales, such as those in [[Denbighshire]], is only believed to have developed within the last 300 years.  Sheep farmers often practised [[transhumance]], with part of each household moving to live in the hills with the sheep during the summer; later, their seasonal hillside ''[[transhumance#Wales|hafod]]''s or dwellings became permanent homes.  In the past, grazing rights were determined by local courts.<ref name=foodmonth>{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/local-news/welsh-food-month-how-lamb-2020740|title= Welsh Food Month: How our lamb came to rule the world|date=11 October 2012|accessdate=27 June 2013|publisher=Media Wales}}</ref>\n\nHistorically, Welsh sheep were shorn twice in the year. Besides the regular shearing in May or June, the [[wool]] was clipped close about the neck and forequarters at [[Michaelmas]], otherwise all of it would have been lost before the following summer in the wanderings of the animal among the thickets and [[furze]] in search of food during winter and spring.<ref name=\"Youatt1840\">{{cite book|last=Youatt|first=William|title=Sheep: Their Breeds, Management, and Diseases : to which is Added the Mountain Shepherd's Manual|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iCFCAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA275|edition=Public domain|year=1840|publisher=Baldwin and Cradock|pages=275\u2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Glamorganshire]] mountain sheep wandered over the countryside from early times, some being horned and others being polled. In the 1840s, Youatt described the sheep of Glamorganshire: \"Some are nearly white, and others are between a dirty white and a perfect black. The head is small; the neck long, erect, and delicate; the fore-quarters light, with narrow breast and shoulders; the sides flat; the back and loins narrow; the legs slight and long; the animals possessing considerable agility. The fleece weighs about {{convert|2|lbs|kg}}. On the [[Gelligaer]] and [[Eglwysilan]] mountains the quality of the wool is fine; but on the hills lying on the western side of the [[River Taff|Taff valley]] it is [[Kemp (wool)|kempy]], which deteriorates its value. The breech wool is still more hairy and coarse.\"<ref name=Youatt1840 /> [[Dre-fach Felindre]] in the Teifi valley became known as the \"[[Huddersfield#Industry|Huddersfield]] of Wales\" when the wool industry was prosperous there.<ref name=Museum>{{Cite web|url=http://www.museumwales.ac.uk/en/wool/about/|title= Discover the spellbinding story of the Welsh woolen industry National Wool Museum|accessdate=26 June 2013|publisher=Official Website of National Wool Museum}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1840s, the hills of [[Montgomeryshire]] included flocks from the low country. Towards the south and west, a smaller white-faced breed was more prevalent while in the north-east a black-faced native breed was found. The breed in the valleys had been improved, principally by sheep from Shropshire. The sheep on the higher grounds weighed about 10&nbsp;lbs. the quarter, while those in the valleys weighed 12 to 14&nbsp;lbs. The lambing season at that time was in March and lambs were shorn in August.<ref name=Youatt1840 /> There were fewer sheep in Denbighshire and [[Flintshire]], particularly in Flintshire, than in any of the other counties, and these were mixed with English breeds. Their weight varied between 10 and 20&nbsp;lbs. per quarter, and the fleece from 2 to 5&nbsp;lbs.<ref name=Youatt1840 />\n\n==Husbandry and economics==\n[[File:Flock of sheep in Ceredigion.jpg|thumb|right|Sheep at Ty'n-y-Cornel farm, near [[Tregaron]] in West Wales]]\n[[File:Counting sheep at Newport Cattle Market - geograph.org.uk - 995447.jpg|thumb|right|Sheep auction at the Cattle Market in [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], which closed in 2009 after 165 years of trading]]\nTwenty percent of all agricultural work is made up by sheep farming. There are over 11 million sheep in the entire country.<ref name=Sheep>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/sheep-farming-wales-way-slaughterhouse-1063268#|title= Is Sheep Farming In Wales On The Way To The Slaughterhouse?|date=6 February 2013|accessdate=26 June 2013|publisher=International Business Times}}</ref><ref name=welshgovernment/> Breeds favoured by modern wool producers, which originate from Wales, include the [[Badger Face Welsh Mountain]], the [[Balwen Welsh Mountain]] and the [[Black Welsh Mountain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wooldirectory.org.uk/wool%20producers.html|title=Producers|publisher=Wool Directory|accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nSheep farming in the mountains of Wales is an arduous task, particularly when the traditional techniques of farming are followed. The activities of sheep farming start with growing grass on the meadows, buying hay from external sources and stacking them. The season starts with the birth of the lambs during spring and continues with feeding, caring, shearing and transportation to market centers, maintaining the fencing around the pens, and taking care of the deserted young lambs or injured lambs. Farms are mostly under small farmers and it is one individual who bears most responsibilities. The sheep farmers' best support is the sheepdog for moving the flocks to better ground or to wintering areas in the valleys, and even in giving them organic treatments in the form of injections and treatments.<ref name=Farming>{{Cite web|url=http://www.environmentalgraffiti.com/animals/news-counting-sheep|title=The Reality of Sheep Farming in the Welsh Mountains|accessdate=26 June 2013|publisher=Environmentalgraffiti.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827144356/http://www.environmentalgraffiti.com/animals/news-counting-sheep|archivedate=27 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years, sheep farming has become less profitable to the farmers for many reasons including the falling prices of lamb meat, weather conditions, loss of more than 1-million breeding [[Sheep|ewes]] between 2001 and 2009 and global warming. The threat of the United Kingdom withdrawing from the [[European Union]] is also a fear for the farmers of Welsh as they anticipate \"doom the Welsh sheep industry\". The EU support to the Welsh rural community is reported to be of the order of about half a billion euros a year. The loss on this account could be an additional burden of \u00a340 per lamb on the farmers. Government support has been sought in the way of subsidies and technical support.<ref name=Sheep/>  Disaster struck parts of Wales in March 2013 when the coldest weather experienced in 50 years caused the deaths of many sheep and lambs and hardship to sheep farmers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-22104293|title=Welsh sheep farms pushed to brink|date= 11 April 2013|accessdate=26 June 2013|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[Welsh Government]]:<ref name=welshgovernment>[http://www.assemblywales.org/bus-home/bus-business-fourth-assembly-written-ministerial-statements/dat20130129-e1.pdf?langoption=3&ttl=Support%20for%20lamb%20producers%20(PDF%2C%20100KB) Welsh Government, ''Support for lamb producers: Statement by Alun Davies AM'', 29 January 2013]. Retrieved 6 July 2013</ref><blockquote>\"Food production is part of the fabric of Wales and the Welsh economy. In 2011 the sheep sector was worth \u00a3270 million \u2013 20 percent of the gross  agricultural output of Wales. But of course its value to Wales goes far beyond its financial worth. Its role in sustaining rural and upland communities and their position as part of our social and cultural fabric is priceless.\"</blockquote>\n\n==Environmental impact==\nThe economic viability of sheep farming in Wales is highly dependent upon the single farm payment given by European taxpayers to people who own land on condition they keep it in \"Good Agricultural and Environmental Condition\".  However, this requires the removal of unwanted vegetation such as wild plants.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/georgemonbiot/2013/may/22/britain-uplands-farming-subsidies Why Britain's barren uplands have farming subsidies to blame], Guardian 22 May 2012, retrieved 5 July 2012</ref> The writer  [[George Monbiot]] claims that sheep farming practices and grazing prevents natural trees and shrubs from growing and the subsequent fauna associated with such ecosystems flourishing, and that sheep compact the soil contributing to a cycle of flood and drought, thereby restricting the productivity of more fertile lands downstream.  Wales imports seven times as much meat as it exports despite 76% of the land in Wales being devoted to livestock farming.<ref>[http://www.monbiot.com/2013/05/30/sheepwrecked/ Sheepwrecked], George Monbiot, 30 May 2012, Retrieved 5 July 2012</ref>\n\nThe [[RSPB]]'s ''State of Nature'' report found that 60% of animal and plant species in Wales have declined over the last 50 years and 31% have declined strongly with farming practices being blamed for loss of habitats.<ref>[http://www.rspb.org.uk/Images/wales_tcm9-345854.pdf  RSPB, ''State of Nature: Wales'']</ref> However, the [[National Farmers Union of England and Wales|National Farmers' Union]] (NFU) said it was \"unfair to conveniently lay the blame on farming\".  NFU Cymru president Ed Bailey said that \u201cmany farmers and visitors to the countryside will be surprised about the report's findings given the huge effort farmers now place on managing the environment\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-22621193 State of Nature report: Wildlife 'at crisis point' in Wales], BBC News Wales, 22 May 2013, Retrieved 5 July 2012</ref>\n\n==Cultural significance==\nThe [[National Wool Museum]] of Wales is located in [[Dre-fach Felindre]], near [[Llandysul]] in [[Carmarthenshire]] and is part of the [[National Museum Wales]]. After refurbishing, the museum was reopened in 2004.<ref name=Museum/>   Sheep farming is closely associated with Wales culturally and is often the subject of \"lewd jokes and anti-Welsh sentiment\" especially by the English.<ref name=\"Hurdley2013\">{{cite book|last=Hurdley|first=Rachel|title=Home, Materiality, Memory and Belonging: Keeping Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L66Iq_f1epQC&pg=PT160|accessdate=23 June 2013|date=7 May 2013|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-1-137-34107-5|page=160}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Sheep in Wales}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-22104293 BBC video on Welsh sheep farming in 2013]\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/learning/teachers/media/pages/geography_econactivity_life.shtml Sheep Farming in Snowdonia]\n* [http://www.museumwales.ac.uk/en/wool/ National Wool Museum, Dre-fach Felindre]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110827144356/http://www.environmentalgraffiti.com/animals/news-counting-sheep The Reality of Sheep Farming in the Welsh Mountains]\n\n{{Wales topics}}\n\n[[Category:Sheep]]\n[[Category:Economy of Wales]]\n[[Category:Agriculture in Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2014}}\n[[File:Curious Sheep - geograph.org.uk - 370174.jpg|thumb|right|Sheep in a field near [[Aberystwyth]]]]\n'''Sheep farming''' is important to the [[economy of Wales]]. Much of [[Wales]] is rural countryside and [[sheep]] are a very common feature in the landscape throughout the country. The [[woollen industry in Wales]] was a major contributor to the national economy, accounting for two-thirds of the nation's exports in 1660. Sheep farms are most often situated in the country's mountains and moorlands, where [[Herding dog|sheepdog]]s are employed to round up flocks. Sheep are also reared, however, along the south and west coasts of Wales.<ref name=\"Colson2011\">{{cite book|last=Colson|first=Mary|title=Wales|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FuK6lZf5Yh0C&pg=PA15|date=1 July 2011|publisher=Heinemann Library|isbn=978-1-4329-5242-6|pages=15\u2013}}</ref> In 2017 there were more than 10 million sheep in Wales and the total flock made up nearly 33% of the British total.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-42371973|title=Sheep numbers pass 10 million mark|date=15 December 2017|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> In 2011 sheep farming accounted for 80% of agriculture in Wales.{{cn|date=October 2018}}\n\n==Historical development==\n[[File:Badgerface ewe, Wales.jpg|right|thumb|A [[Badger Face Welsh Mountain]] ewe on [[Flat Holm]]]]\n[[File:Springtime scene - geograph.org.uk - 383776.jpg|thumb|Sheep and lambs near [[Brecon]] in early spring]]\nSheep farming is an ancient husbandry activity in rural parts of Wales where the climate and soil conditions were not suitable for growing crops other than [[oats]]. The activity is documented from mediaeval times, by which time white sheep probably imported by the Romans had interbred with native dark-fleeced types to produce varieties of [[Welsh Mountain sheep]]. Initially, sheep were bred for their milk and [[wool|fleece]]s, rather than their meat.<ref name=foodmonth/>\n\nBy the 13th century, sheep farming in  Wales had become a major industry and source of income, largely from wool, much of which was exported.  Large flocks of sheep were owned by [[Cistercian]] [[abbey]]s and [[monastery|monasteries]], such as those at [[Strata Florida]], [[Margam Abbey|Margam]], [[Basingwerk Abbey|Basingwerk]] and [[Tintern Abbey|Tintern]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XSE9AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA410&dq=wales+sheep+farming+history&hl=en&sa=X&ei=e0PMUcPaMMme0wW3uoHIAw&ved=0CDAQ6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=wales%20sheep&f=false  H.E. Hallam (ed.), ''The Agrarian history of England and Wales: 1042-1350'', pp.479-480]</ref><ref>[http://www.bahs.org.uk/AGHR/ARTICLES/06n1a1.pdf  R. A. Donkin, ''Cistercian Sheep, Farming and Wool-Sales in the Thirteenth Century'', The Agricultural History Review, vol.6, 1958, pp.2-8]. Retrieved 27 June 2013</ref>  The [[woollen industry in Wales]] was a major contributor to the national economy, accounting for two-thirds of the nation's exports in 1660.<ref name=Sheep/>  However, large-scale sheep rearing on the higher moors of Wales, such as those in [[Denbighshire]], is only believed to have developed within the last 300 years.  Sheep farmers often practised [[transhumance]], with part of each household moving to live in the hills with the sheep during the summer; later, their seasonal hillside ''[[transhumance#Wales|hafod]]''s or dwellings became permanent homes.  In the past, grazing rights were determined by local courts.<ref name=foodmonth>{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/local-news/welsh-food-month-how-lamb-2020740|title= Welsh Food Month: How our lamb came to rule the world|date=11 October 2012|accessdate=27 June 2013|publisher=Media Wales}}</ref>\n\nHistorically, Welsh sheep were shorn twice in the year. Besides the regular shearing in May or June, the [[wool]] was clipped close about the neck and forequarters at [[Michaelmas]], otherwise all of it would have been lost before the following summer in the wanderings of the animal among the thickets and [[furze]] in search of food during winter and spring.<ref name=\"Youatt1840\">{{cite book|last=Youatt|first=William|title=Sheep: Their Breeds, Management, and Diseases : to which is Added the Mountain Shepherd's Manual|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iCFCAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA275|edition=Public domain|year=1840|publisher=Baldwin and Cradock|pages=275\u2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Glamorganshire]] mountain sheep wandered over the countryside from early times, some being horned and others being polled. In the 1840s, Youatt described the sheep of Glamorganshire: \"Some are nearly white, and others are between a dirty white and a perfect black. The head is small; the neck long, erect, and delicate; the fore-quarters light, with narrow breast and shoulders; the sides flat; the back and loins narrow; the legs slight and long; the animals possessing considerable agility. The fleece weighs about {{convert|2|lbs|kg}}. On the [[Gelligaer]] and [[Eglwysilan]] mountains the quality of the wool is fine; but on the hills lying on the western side of the [[River Taff|Taff valley]] it is [[Kemp (wool)|kempy]], which deteriorates its value. The breech wool is still more hairy and coarse.\"<ref name=Youatt1840 /> [[Dre-fach Felindre]] in the Teifi valley became known as the \"[[Huddersfield#Industry|Huddersfield]] of Wales\" when the wool industry was prosperous there.<ref name=Museum>{{Cite web|url=http://www.museumwales.ac.uk/en/wool/about/|title= Discover the spellbinding story of the Welsh woolen industry National Wool Museum|accessdate=26 June 2013|publisher=Official Website of National Wool Museum}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1840s, the hills of [[Montgomeryshire]] included flocks from the low country. Towards the south and west, a smaller white-faced breed was more prevalent while in the north-east a black-faced native breed was found. The breed in the valleys had been improved, principally by sheep from Shropshire. The sheep on the higher grounds weighed about 10&nbsp;lbs. the quarter, while those in the valleys weighed 12 to 14&nbsp;lbs. The lambing season at that time was in March and lambs were shorn in August.<ref name=Youatt1840 /> There were fewer sheep in Denbighshire and [[Flintshire]], particularly in Flintshire, than in any of the other counties, and these were mixed with English breeds. Their weight varied between 10 and 20&nbsp;lbs. per quarter, and the fleece from 2 to 5&nbsp;lbs.<ref name=Youatt1840 />\n\n==Husbandry and economics==\n[[File:\"Why has Nigel locked our Mums in there\" - geograph.org.uk - 1423470.jpg|thumb|right|Sheep at Ty'n-y-Cornel farm, near [[Tregaron]] in West Wales]]\n[[File:Counting sheep at Newport Cattle Market - geograph.org.uk - 995447.jpg|thumb|right|Sheep auction at the Cattle Market in [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], which closed in 2009 after 165 years of trading]]\nTwenty percent of all agricultural work is made up by sheep farming. There are over 11 million sheep in the entire country.<ref name=Sheep>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/sheep-farming-wales-way-slaughterhouse-1063268#|title= Is Sheep Farming In Wales On The Way To The Slaughterhouse?|date=6 February 2013|accessdate=26 June 2013|publisher=International Business Times}}</ref><ref name=welshgovernment/> Breeds favoured by modern wool producers, which originate from Wales, include the [[Badger Face Welsh Mountain]], the [[Balwen Welsh Mountain]] and the [[Black Welsh Mountain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wooldirectory.org.uk/wool%20producers.html|title=Producers|publisher=Wool Directory|accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nSheep farming in the mountains of Wales is an arduous task, particularly when the traditional techniques of farming are followed. The activities of sheep farming start with growing grass on the meadows, buying hay from external sources and stacking them. The season starts with the birth of the lambs during spring and continues with feeding, caring, shearing and transportation to market centers, maintaining the fencing around the pens, and taking care of the deserted young lambs or injured lambs. Farms are mostly under small farmers and it is one individual who bears most responsibilities. The sheep farmers' best support is the sheepdog for moving the flocks to better ground or to wintering areas in the valleys, and even in giving them organic treatments in the form of injections and treatments.<ref name=Farming>{{Cite web|url=http://www.environmentalgraffiti.com/animals/news-counting-sheep|title=The Reality of Sheep Farming in the Welsh Mountains|accessdate=26 June 2013|publisher=Environmentalgraffiti.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827144356/http://www.environmentalgraffiti.com/animals/news-counting-sheep|archivedate=27 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years, sheep farming has become less profitable to the farmers for many reasons including the falling prices of lamb meat, weather conditions, loss of more than 1-million breeding [[Sheep|ewes]] between 2001 and 2009 and global warming. The threat of the United Kingdom withdrawing from the [[European Union]] is also a fear for the farmers of Welsh as they anticipate \"doom the Welsh sheep industry\". The EU support to the Welsh rural community is reported to be of the order of about half a billion euros a year. The loss on this account could be an additional burden of \u00a340 per lamb on the farmers. Government support has been sought in the way of subsidies and technical support.<ref name=Sheep/>  Disaster struck parts of Wales in March 2013 when the coldest weather experienced in 50 years caused the deaths of many sheep and lambs and hardship to sheep farmers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-22104293|title=Welsh sheep farms pushed to brink|date= 11 April 2013|accessdate=26 June 2013|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[Welsh Government]]:<ref name=welshgovernment>[http://www.assemblywales.org/bus-home/bus-business-fourth-assembly-written-ministerial-statements/dat20130129-e1.pdf?langoption=3&ttl=Support%20for%20lamb%20producers%20(PDF%2C%20100KB) Welsh Government, ''Support for lamb producers: Statement by Alun Davies AM'', 29 January 2013]. Retrieved 6 July 2013</ref><blockquote>\"Food production is part of the fabric of Wales and the Welsh economy. In 2011 the sheep sector was worth \u00a3270 million \u2013 20 percent of the gross  agricultural output of Wales. But of course its value to Wales goes far beyond its financial worth. Its role in sustaining rural and upland communities and their position as part of our social and cultural fabric is priceless.\"</blockquote>\n\n==Environmental impact==\nThe economic viability of sheep farming in Wales is highly dependent upon the single farm payment given by European taxpayers to people who own land on condition they keep it in \"Good Agricultural and Environmental Condition\".  However, this requires the removal of unwanted vegetation such as wild plants.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/georgemonbiot/2013/may/22/britain-uplands-farming-subsidies Why Britain's barren uplands have farming subsidies to blame], Guardian 22 May 2012, retrieved 5 July 2012</ref> The writer  [[George Monbiot]] claims that sheep farming practices and grazing prevents natural trees and shrubs from growing and the subsequent fauna associated with such ecosystems flourishing, and that sheep compact the soil contributing to a cycle of flood and drought, thereby restricting the productivity of more fertile lands downstream.  Wales imports seven times as much meat as it exports despite 76% of the land in Wales being devoted to livestock farming.<ref>[http://www.monbiot.com/2013/05/30/sheepwrecked/ Sheepwrecked], George Monbiot, 30 May 2012, Retrieved 5 July 2012</ref>\n\nThe [[RSPB]]'s ''State of Nature'' report found that 60% of animal and plant species in Wales have declined over the last 50 years and 31% have declined strongly with farming practices being blamed for loss of habitats.<ref>[http://www.rspb.org.uk/Images/wales_tcm9-345854.pdf  RSPB, ''State of Nature: Wales'']</ref> However, the [[National Farmers Union of England and Wales|National Farmers' Union]] (NFU) said it was \"unfair to conveniently lay the blame on farming\".  NFU Cymru president Ed Bailey said that \u201cmany farmers and visitors to the countryside will be surprised about the report's findings given the huge effort farmers now place on managing the environment\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-22621193 State of Nature report: Wildlife 'at crisis point' in Wales], BBC News Wales, 22 May 2013, Retrieved 5 July 2012</ref>\n\n==Cultural significance==\nThe [[National Wool Museum]] of Wales is located in [[Dre-fach Felindre]], near [[Llandysul]] in [[Carmarthenshire]] and is part of the [[National Museum Wales]]. After refurbishing, the museum was reopened in 2004.<ref name=Museum/>   Sheep farming is closely associated with Wales culturally and is often the subject of \"lewd jokes and anti-Welsh sentiment\" especially by the English.<ref name=\"Hurdley2013\">{{cite book|last=Hurdley|first=Rachel|title=Home, Materiality, Memory and Belonging: Keeping Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L66Iq_f1epQC&pg=PT160|accessdate=23 June 2013|date=7 May 2013|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-1-137-34107-5|page=160}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Sheep in Wales}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-22104293 BBC video on Welsh sheep farming in 2013]\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/learning/teachers/media/pages/geography_econactivity_life.shtml Sheep Farming in Snowdonia]\n* [http://www.museumwales.ac.uk/en/wool/ National Wool Museum, Dre-fach Felindre]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110827144356/http://